{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640570"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:18:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:18:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17838"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17838"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10552"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116722"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10552"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17838"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98710"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"10059"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24610"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116722"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA student is learning about sugar transport across cell membranes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following transporters is responsible for releasing absorbed sugars from the intestinal mucosa into the circulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["GLUT2","GLUT3","GLUT4","GLUT5","SGLT"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests understanding of membrane transport proteins involved in sugar absorption. \u003Cstrong\u003EGLUT2\u003C/strong\u003E is the transporter responsible for moving glucose, galactose, and fructose from the enterocytes of the intestinal mucosa into the bloodstream. It facilitates the passive transport of these sugars down their concentration gradient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGLUT3\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily found in neurons and is responsible for the uptake of glucose into the brain, not the intestines. \u003Cstrong\u003EGLUT4\u003C/strong\u003E is an insulin-regulated glucose transporter found in adipose tissue and striated muscle, including cardiac and skeletal muscle. It is not involved in the transport of sugars from the intestinal mucosa. \u003Cstrong\u003EGLUT5\u003C/strong\u003E is a fructose transporter located on the apical membrane of enterocytes, facilitating the uptake of fructose into the cells, but not its release into the bloodstream. \u003Cstrong\u003ESGLT\u003C/strong\u003E (Sodium-Glucose Linked Transporter) is involved in the active transport of glucose and galactose into the enterocytes from the intestinal lumen, using a sodium gradient, but not in their release into the circulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["GLUT2 is responsible for the transport of glucose, galactose, and fructose from the intestinal mucosa into the bloodstream.","GLUT transporters are specific to different tissues and have distinct roles in glucose metabolism.","SGLT is involved in the active transport of glucose and galactose into the enterocytes, not their release into circulation."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 66; pg. 831.","Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040568."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"typ